When TIR happens, there are evanescent waves48 penetrating into air with a limited spatial distance (in the order of wavelengths). The scattering is induced by the following processes: the evanescent wave is coupled into silica microspheres, then re-emitted out of the spheres. The profiles of evanescent wave can be seen from the red parts near the interface in Fig. 10. The sphere with the diameter of 0.3 μ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mu $$\end{document}m is so small, that it induces small modifications of the evanescent wave [Fig. 10(a)]. When the diameters become larger, the spheres lead to significant modifications of the evanescent wave [Fig. 10(b–d)]. As the plane wave propagates from left to right, the evanescent wave is effectively coupled into the spheres to the right of the contact points. If several microspheres aggregate together, the profile of the evanescent wave is different from the case of single spheres [Fig. 10(e)]. A great part of the evanescent wave near the aggregation is still coupled into the spheres and re-emitted into air.

